But I am also aware of Eckhart Tolle's story where he basically only got self-realized on the brink of surrendering himself to serious emotional distress. Perhaps it is the motivation that causes that, for me I was not trying to escape any suffering but it was much more just genuine curiosity.

In a sense, if you knew exactly what self-image is, you would be self-realized. Your job is to figure out what self-image truly is by noticing the symptoms (emotions, incongruent thoughts) that it creates in your experience and then asking yourself how that occurs. That is self-inquiry.

To add on to this, perhaps this is a bit tangential, but in regards to aims that people have, people often talk about being confused in identifying self-image. You don't need a concrete idea or definition of self-image to really inquire about it, because you still know exactly when it appears. You know when you get emotional about the future. You know when you feel social anxiety. You know that is all self-image without having it perfectly defined in your mind. Question those experiences and how they operate, that is all self-inquiry is.

I would say shame is like a feeling of "I didn't do good enough", which could be invoked by the expectations of others, but not necessarily. You can have expectations from others which cause other emotions, like anger, fear, etc.

I find the distinctions between guilt and shame to be a bit superfluous in hindsight. They all involve feeling bad because you want to change something you don't believe you did well enough. If you feel guilty, that is synonymous with shame and you regret what you have done. If there is guilt, all three of those emotions/desires occur simultaneously.

Regret on the other hand seems different than the others, although it can invoke them or occur alongside them. Regret by itself is neutral. If the regret involves alleviating the hurt you are causing others, then it becomes paired with shame or guilt and it actually becomes synonymous with those things. Shame and guilt are a specific form of regret. If the regret involves something you did in high school or something that is purely of the past, It is a recognition that you would not currently do what you did in the past. With shame/guilt, it is recognizing that you should undo what has occurred in the past. But with regret by itself, it is recognizing that you shouldn't do what has occurred in the past. The former involves the opportunity to reverse or alleviate the decision you made, whereas the latter is knowledge or understanding about what decisions you should and shouldn't make. The latter would not necessarily create guilt or shame, it is similar to just having intelligence or knowledge about something.
